{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504130"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:11:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:11:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2302"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2302"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.12,0.04,0.28,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44862"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2302"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29749"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1215"},{"type":"tags","id":"6295"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44862"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents with an inability to fully use the ring finger on her left hand. She remembers injuring this finger whilst playing netball three months ago. There is no pain in the finger or any of her joints. She is otherwise in good health with no significant medical history or any family history of autoimmune diseases. On examination of her hands, there is a loss of extension her fourth digit proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joint (Image) and extended distal interphalangeal (DIP) joint. The Elson test is positive. There are no other tender or swollen joints in the hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is most likely to have been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proximal interphalangeal collateral ligament","Flexor digitorum superficialis tendon","Distal interphalangeal lateral band","Proximal interphalangeal central slip","Extensor digitorum superficialis tendon"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a boutonniere deformity, which can result from injury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eproximal interphalangeal central slip\u003C/strong\u003E. Boutonniere deformity presents with PIP flexion and DIP extension. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Elson test is a good test for proximal interphalangeal central slip injuries. The test involves the patient placing their affected finger over the edge of a table, so that their PIP joint is flexed at 90 degrees. The clinician then puts some resistance over the middle phalanx, and asks the patient to extend their finger. It is positive when only weak extension is felt at the PIP, and there is hyperextension at the DIP. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Elson test would not be positive in an injury of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eextensor digitorum superficialis tendon\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAside from traumatic avulsions, other conditions that cause boutonniere deformity include rheumatoid arthritis (common) and lacerations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDamage to the proximal \u003Cstrong\u003Einterphalangeal collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E would cause any three of the following hand examination findings:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Easymmetric swelling and tenderness over the collateral ligament without instability on the lateral stress test\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ea stable active arc of motion and deviation with a firm on the lateral stress test\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esubluxation or dislocation on active extension and joint laxity on varus and valgus stress test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInjury to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor digitorum superficialis tendon\u003C/strong\u003E will cause trigger finger. Patients may complain of pain at the level of A1 pulley and/or referred pain to the dorsal metacarpal phalangeal region or PIP region, clicking sensation, crepitus, catching, \u003Cem\u003Ea \u0027locked\u0027, flexed finger at the PIP joint.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Boutonniere deformity is where the PIP is flexed and the DIP is extended.","Injury to the proximal interphalangeal central slip results in Boutonniere\u0027s deformity and a positive Elson test."],"references":["Firtha, M., Roth, A. and Fei, T. (no date) Boutonniere deformity, Orthobullets. Available at: https://www.orthobullets.com/hand/6012/boutonniere-deformity (Accessed: December 8, 2022).","KC;, K.S.H.H.E.C. (no date) Complications of proximal interphalangeal joint injuries: Prevention and treatment, Hand clinics. U.S. National Library of Medicine. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29625645/ (Accessed: December 8, 2022).","Team, O., Gokkus, K. and Anonymous, - (no date) Trigger finger, Orthobullets. Available at: https://www.orthobullets.com/hand/6027/trigger-finger (Accessed: December 8, 2022)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29749"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2302"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19661"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19661"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/260c0d4d-f727-46bf-beea-1ae4bb13e753.jpg","thumbUrl":"